you're 79 years old...

08:16.062 --> 08:18.656
and you're convinced that
you've been seeing U.F.O.s.

08:18.731 --> 08:21.529
I did see one. Uh, yeah. But see,
that's what happens to you, Sam.

08:21.601 --> 08:25.594
Ziggy says your memory is Swiss-cheesed
with the real Mr. Stoddard,

08:25.671 --> 08:30.404
who, by the way right now, is in the waiting
room and he thinks he's on his way to Venus.

08:30.476 --> 08:33.570
Guy must be terrified. Au
contraire. He's in heaven.

08:33.645 --> 08:36.672
He keeps fingering our clothes.
He wants to know what we eat.

08:36.749 --> 08:39.946
You know what he says to me?
He says- He says, "Take me to your leader. "

08:40.019 --> 08:43.419
So I turned him over to Gooshie. Told him
he was the king of the planet Halitosis.

08:43.489 --> 08:47.016
Al, I've got to find a way
to get back to those woods.

08:47.093 --> 08:50.756
Because there has to be some
kind of physical evidence there-

08:50.830 --> 08:53.025
<i>That's exactly what
you should not do.</i>

08:53.099 --> 08:55.590
No, no, no, no. See, you don't
realize what I've discovered. No, Sam,

08:55.668 --> 08:58.899
you don't realize that in
less than a week, your son, John,

08:58.971 --> 09:02.702
is gonna have you committed
to the local mental hospital.

09:02.775 --> 09:07.610
<i>Just because I saw a U.F.O.? No. Because Max saw
- Max thinks he saw a U.F.O.</i>

09:07.680 --> 09:11.810
And he's been blabbing about it to everybody,
including the parish priest, the ice cream man-

09:11.884 --> 09:13.818
Al, the man is no more
crazy than I am.

09:13.886 --> 09:16.218
And if I can get back to those woods,
I can prove it to you.

09:16.289 --> 09:20.282
That's all we need is for you to go traipsing
through the underbrush in your long johns.

09:20.359 --> 09:23.419
That'll get you into
the hospital even sooner.

09:23.496 --> 09:26.431
Are you sure? I mean, is Ziggy
sure that that's why I'm here?

09:26.499 --> 09:28.865
Uh, 78.1%.

09:28.935 --> 09:32.302
What are the odds of me being here to
prove the existence of extraterrestrials?

09:32.371 --> 09:36.501
Uh, 73.3%. I win!
Yeah, but it's very close.

09:36.576 --> 09:40.103
This isn't horseshoes, Sam. You know Ziggy.
She'll come up with one figure one minute...

09:40.179 --> 09:43.273
and the next, she'll have a whole new
calculation. Sam, you're not being objective.

09:43.349 --> 09:46.512
I'm a scientist. Scientists are
objective. You're not being objective.

09:46.586 --> 09:50.647
Are you kidding? If all scientists were
objective, we wouldn't have the lightbulb.

09:50.723 --> 09:52.657
We never would have
even landed on the moon.

09:52.725 --> 09:54.852
This is '66. You got three years
before you go to the moon.

09:54.927 --> 09:57.794
And I would not be traveling around in time.
You gotta have the dream first, Al.

09:57.863 --> 10:01.629
Great scientists are never objective. And that's
why people always think that they're loony.

10:01.701 --> 10:05.034
Which is exactly
what they think about Max.

10:05.104 --> 10:08.164
But don't you see-

10:08.240 --> 10:10.504
<i>I mean, don't you get it, Al?</i>

10:10.576 --> 10:13.010
You see, a discovery like this-
I mean, it could mean-

10:13.079 --> 10:18.915
<i>I feel the way I felt the first time I saw
my time-travel calculations working.</i>

10:18.985 --> 10:24.321
I'm so unbelievably lucky to
- to be there on the cutting edge of solving one of mankind's oldest riddles.

10:24.390 --> 10:28.258
And now
- now I have a chance to solve a second one in the same lifetime.

10:28.327 --> 10:30.318
I mean-

10:30.396 --> 10:34.662
Nobody gets that chance.
Nobody.

10:37.737 --> 10:40.570
Oh, God.
John.

10:40.640 --> 10:45.168
He's gotten worse. We just can't
give him the care that he needs.

10:45.244 --> 10:50.546
He'll be miserable in a hospital.
We don't have a choice.

10:50.616 --> 10:52.607
Oh.

11:00.359 --> 11:05.956
<i>I was up at dawn dying to prove that
what I'd seen in the woods last night was real.</i>

11:06.032 --> 11:11.664
<i>And then if I could reconcile Tim and his dad in
