You go out your bedroom window tonight, you get
as far as the corner market, they pick you up.

17:48.000 --> 17:51.902
What happens to Max? What if they don't
pick me up, huh? What if I don't get caught?

17:55.274 --> 17:59.108
I changed my mind.
You are crazy.

18:00.179 --> 18:03.114
This is pointless.
The old man's coming unglued.

18:03.182 --> 18:05.412
We don't know that for sure.

18:06.518 --> 18:12.150
Come on. When you're riding alone in a car,
don't you ever rehearse conversations...

18:12.224 --> 18:14.920
<i>or things you wish you'd said?
Yeah. Sure I do.</i>

18:14.993 --> 18:17.928
But he's not in a car.
He's on a public dock.

18:17.996 --> 18:20.863
<i>And I usually don't wave my arms
and pace around like a caged animal.</i>

18:20.933 --> 18:23.299
Next thing you know,
he'll be foaming at the mouth.

18:23.368 --> 18:26.826
Look, I don't try to play soldier.
Why don't you quit playing psychiatrist?

18:26.905 --> 18:29.305
I say we classify him "Not Relevant"
and head back to D.C.

18:29.374 --> 18:32.366
- We've got plenty of other subjects.
- Not who've kept notes like Stoddard,

18:32.444 --> 18:34.378
<i>or written articles.</i>

18:34.446 --> 18:38.280
<i>Frankly, I find his theory of return U.F.O.
Visitations in this area quite coherent.</i>

18:38.350 --> 18:40.284
<i>Yeah. Alice In Wonderland
is coherent too.</i>

18:40.352 --> 18:43.378
- That doesn't mean I believe in grinning cats who disappear.
- You give up too easily.

18:43.455 --> 18:47.949
<i>Are you seriously gonna put your signature on a report
about a man whose own son wants to have him committed?</i>

18:48.026 --> 18:51.359
<i>Not unless I can verify
his testimony with other ways.</i>

18:51.430 --> 18:54.331
- You know I don't like those other ways.
- They work, Major.

18:54.399 --> 18:59.803
<i>I think maybe the state hospital Just might be
the safest place for Maxwell Stoddard after all.</i>

19:13.852 --> 19:16.480
<i>Hey, Tim, I was think-</i>

19:19.057 --> 19:23.016
Going somewhere? Uh, yeah,
um, camping with the guys.

19:23.095 --> 19:26.587
Um, we're, you know, hanging out,
maybe catch some fish.

19:26.665 --> 19:29.099
How come you're home early?

19:29.168 --> 19:33.935
I thought you and I were supposed
to have a real, honest relationship.

19:34.006 --> 19:36.372
We do.

19:36.441 --> 19:38.500
You're not going camping.

19:38.577 --> 19:44.015
Okay. Lanny's picking me up tonight,
we're goin' down to the Village.

19:44.082 --> 19:47.279
When are you coming back?
I'm not, Pop.

19:49.955 --> 19:53.618
You're running away? In three months,
I'll be old enough to get drafted.

19:53.692 --> 19:55.683
I'm old enough to
choose my own life.

19:55.761 --> 19:58.457
I agree with that.

19:59.531 --> 20:02.193
You do?
That's great, Pop.

20:02.267 --> 20:05.361
You're also old enough to know that this
is a bad idea. Oh, don't you start on me.

20:05.437 --> 20:08.964
Look, how do you think your dad's gonna feel
when he wakes up tomorrow and you're not here?

20:09.041 --> 20:11.805
Relieved. No way. No way.
And neither is your mom.

20:13.478 --> 20:16.038
Hey, I'll write
as soon as I'm settled.

20:16.114 --> 20:19.743
Look, your dad wants you to stay in school,
right? Right. Right. Community college.

20:19.818 --> 20:23.015
The pits. He just wants to keep me at
home. Maybe that's all he can afford.

20:23.088 --> 20:26.023
They don't even have music classes.

20:26.091 --> 20:31.586
You want to go sleep on sidewalk in
the Village? No way. Lanny's got a van.

20:32.664 --> 20:34.655
What if there was a way
you could do both?

20:35.968 --> 20:40.302
I don't get it. Look, what if you went
to college in New York during the day...

20:40.372 --> 20:42.431
and then you got a job at night
playing the guitar?

20:42.507 --> 20:46.238
You take the money that you earn there
and you put it towards the extra tuition.

20:47.879 --> 20:50.109
No. No. My dad
would never go for it.

20:50.182 --> 20:54.619
Hey, look, you don't know that. Besides, that
depends on how hard we try and sell him on it.

20:54.686 --> 20:58.019
We? Yeah. I'll help you.
I'm sure your mom will too.

20:59.191 --> 21:03.127
I don't know, Pop.
Oh, come on now. Just-

21:03.195 --> 21:06.289
Just think about it, okay?

21:06.365 --> 21:09.425
<i>It's a nice guitar.
Who's your favorite guy?</i>

21:09.501 --> 21:12.163
Lead guy, you know? Chuck
Berry. Keith Richards.

21:12.237 --> 21:15.138
This new guy I haven't told you about
- uh, English guy, Clapton.

21:15.207 --> 21:17.971
Oh, yeah. Yeah.
You ever hear ofJimi Hendrix?

21:18.043 --> 21:20.807
Who's he?
Some old big-band guy?

21:20.879 --> 21:22.813
No, not actually.

21:22.881 --> 21:28.046
If you ever get a chance to hear him play,
you-Wait. You will actually, within the year.

21:28.120 --> 21:30.884
Yeah? Where's he
playing? Woodstock.

21:30.956 --> 21:34.687
Oh, right. There's nothing up there but
farms, Pop. Who's gonna listen, the cows?

21:34.760 --> 21:38.560
Trust me on this, okay?
What's he sound like?

21:43.669 --> 21:47.036
Well, he-he kind of-
Plug that thing in.

21:47.105 --> 21:51.041
Let me see if I can, uh- It's been
a while but, uh- Turn the radio off.

21:56.148 --> 21:58.343
All right. Here we go.

21:59.651 --> 22:02.916
Pop, Pop, be careful.
I just had it fixed.

22:46.998 --> 22:50.058
What the hell is this?

22:50.135 --> 22:52.797
Uh, just a little, uh,
dem-demonstration.

22:52.871 --> 22:56.068
Of what?
A cat in a garbage disposal?

23:00.846 --> 23:04.009
S- Sorry, I- I, uh-

23:04.082 --> 23:06.414
That's okay.
Forget it, Pop.

23:14.226 --> 23:17.252
I can't remember the last time
I had a meal this good.

23:17.329 --> 23:19.297
Thank you, Max.

23:20.365 --> 23:22.356
Tim, you, uh-

23:24.236 --> 23:27.501
you want to talk about what
we discussed this afternoon?

23:29.608 --> 23:32.873
Honey, are you all right?
You've hardly touched your food.

23:32.944 --> 23:34.935
I'm fine.

23:35.013 --> 23:37.641
Your mother worked hard
to put food on the table.

23:37.716 --> 23:41.413
So that makes me an eating machine?
You'll eat it and be glad you have it.

23:41.486 --> 23:44.353
I'm not three anymore, Dad.

23:46.158 --> 23:48.149
It was about college.

23:48.226 --> 23:53.493
<i>Tim wants to play music. You want him to go
to school. I don't see why he can't do both.</i>

23:53.565 --> 23:58.366
- Well, that sounds sensible.
- I thought you said City College didn't have a music department?

23:58.437 --> 24:00.837
L- I-I don't want to study it, Dad.
I want to play it.

24:00.906 --> 24:05.275
<i>We were talking about using his talent
to help pay part of the tuition...</i>

24:05.343 --> 24:07.368
down in Manhattan.

24:10.148 --> 24:13.948
- We've been through this. - Uh, John,
j-just wait a minute. This sounds different.

24:14.019 --> 24:18.479
<i>People do it, Dad. L
- I can play clubs at night and go to school in the day.</i>

24:18.557 --> 24:21.549
And when do you study?
While you sleep?

24:21.626 --> 24:24.322
I don't understand you,
honestly.

24:24.396 --> 24:29.265
<i>If Pop here had offered to feed me and put
me up while I went to college on his nickel,</i>

24:29.334 --> 24:31.393
don't you think I wouldn't
have jumped at the chance?

24:31.470 --> 24:35.497
News flash, Dad: I'm not you! Don't
you ever use that tone with me again.

24:35.574 --> 24:39.032
Fine.
If that's the way you want it.

24:42.447 --> 24:44.881
Tim Stoddard, get back-

24:44.950 --> 24:47.578
Tim-
Where are you going?

24:47.652 --> 24:50.485
I'm goin' to bring him back.
Don't bother.

24:50.555 --> 24:54.184
- John!
- Well, look at 'em. You see how they gang up on me?

24:54.259 --> 24:56.489
It takes a gang
to get through to you.

25:02.300 --> 25:05.929
<i>Tim! He went that way,
Sam. Down by the water.</i>

25:06.004 --> 25:08.529
Al, have Ziggy run a projection
on Timothy's future.

25:08.607 --> 25:10.768
Well, h-he runs away to Manhattan.

25:10.842 --> 25:15.040
And then he plays in a couple of performances
with a small-time band called River Wind.

25:15.113 --> 25:19.743
And- Uh-oh.
He winds up on a slab at Bellevue.

25:19.818 --> 25:22.343
What?
Overdosed on heroin.

25:25.290 --> 25:27.554
Sam?

25:27.626 --> 25:29.617
<i>Sam.!</i>

25:34.032 --> 25:36.193
<i>Tim?</i>

25:36.268 --> 25:39.101
<i>Hey, Tim.!
It's me, Pop.!</i>

25:40.171 --> 25:42.833
I gotta talk to you.

25:42.908 --> 25:44.899
Tim.

25:50.682 --> 25:54.709
Tim? Tim!
Come on. It's just me!

25:56.588 --> 25:58.647
Why is he such a jerk?

26:01.059 --> 26:04.256
Well, that's- that's my son
you're talking about, you know.

26:04.329 --> 26:08.163
I wanted to tell him. I tried
to tell him. I was there.

26:08.233 --> 26:12.932
And he treats us both like babies. And
you're pushing 80. Doesn't that hack you off?

26:13.004 --> 26:15.097
Yeah.

26:17.709 --> 26:19.939
I just got to get out of that house.

26:21.413 --> 26:23.973
Sam, check this out.
Given this new information,

26:24.049 --> 26:26.950
Ziggy's projecting that
your secondary objective is Tim.

26:27.018 --> 26:29.748
That you gotta prevent him
from O.D.'ing.

26:46.938 --> 26:49.099
You get high, don't you?

26:49.174 --> 26:53.702
- Me? What does that have to do with anything?
- This is just between you and me.

26:53.778 --> 26:59.375
Yeah. I've smoked a few joints in my time. L-I use
it for playing music and for listening. It's great.

26:59.451 --> 27:02.978
- No, it's not great.
- What, you've tried it?

27:04.055 --> 27:06.250
No. No.

27:06.324 --> 27:10.784
L
- I'm just telling you that it's not good, okay, for you or for your music.

27:10.862 --> 27:14.764
L- I can't tell you
the number of- of musicians...

27:14.833 --> 27:17.927
whose-whose lives
have been cut short bec-

27:19.871 --> 27:22.806
Actually, I- I can.

27:22.874 --> 27:26.310
- You rememberJimi Hendrix? I was telling you about him?
- Yeah, what about him?

27:26.378 --> 27:29.074
Okay. Remember his name.
And-And Janis Joplin?

27:29.147 --> 27:33.675
I never heard of her.
Well, um, Jim Morrison.

27:33.752 --> 27:36.152
Uh- Uh, Brian Jones.

27:36.221 --> 27:39.850
- He's in the Stones.
- Was. Is. But- But not for long.

27:39.924 --> 27:43.018
- Elvis.
- Right. And Elvis.

27:43.094 --> 27:45.255
Oh, Pop, you're flippin' out
on me again.

27:45.330 --> 27:48.060
No, I'm telling you,
listen to me.

27:48.133 --> 27:52.695
Everyone of those people I just told you about-
Their deaths are all drug related.

27:52.771 --> 27:55.763
I mean it!

27:58.276 --> 28:01.712
Now- Now listen.

28:01.780 --> 28:04.374
I know this doesn't
make a whole lot of sense,

28:05.717 --> 28:09.949
but if you run off to New York City- whatever
you're gonna do- and I'm not around to help you,

28:10.021 --> 28:14.890
I want you to remember this conversation,
okay, and remember those people's names.

28:14.959 --> 28:20.829
And if you start getting' into drugs, okay, not
just grass, but into heavy drugs and stuff like that,

28:20.899 --> 28:24.733
you look at those people,
you look what happened in their lives,

28:24.803 --> 28:27.704
<i>and you remember that we had this talk.
This is brilliant.</i>

28:27.772 --> 28:30.036
- His odds are improving.
- You promise?

28:30.108 --> 28:32.633
I promise. Okay. Tell
me their names again.

28:32.711 --> 28:35.339
Hendrix. JanetJoplin-
Janis.

28:35.413 --> 28:39.907
Whatever. Elvis, Brian Jones.
Too weird.

28:39.984 --> 28:41.918
Uh, Jim Morrison.
Jim Morrison.

28:41.986 --> 28:45.444
- That's it, Sam. He's- He's safe now.
- Thank God.

28:45.523 --> 28:49.584
Pop, you are the original
space cadet.

28:52.964 --> 28:55.933
If you only knew.
Come on. Let's go home.

28:56.000 --> 28:57.991
Let's get out of here.

29:17.088 --> 29:19.886
<i>Mom, Dad.</i>

29:21.192 --> 29:24.753
- I'm sorry.
- Dad, this is Dr. Hardy.

29:24.829 --> 29:27.059
<i>He's a psychiatrist.
Uh-oh.!</i>

29:27.132 --> 29:30.966
- Mr. Stoddard, so glad to meet you.
- Don't- Don't answer them.

29:32.437 --> 29:35.770
I don't understand.
What's he doing here?

29:35.840 --> 29:41.073
- Pop's not crazy.
- Nobody said he was, son. Major Irwin Meadows, U.S. Air Force Intelligence.

29:41.146 --> 29:43.137
Thank you for allowing us
into your home.

29:43.214 --> 29:45.148
<i>I don't know that I did.
You didn't.</i>

29:45.216 --> 29:48.617
Pop, these men are part of
a special government project.

29:48.686 --> 29:52.520
<i>- Come on. Come sit down.
- Yeah. Watergate was a special project too.</i>

29:52.590 --> 29:56.720
What, uh, sort of
a government project?

29:56.795 --> 30:00.322
We investigate unexplained events that
might have a bearing on national security.

30:00.398 --> 30:04.334
- What kind of events?
- Flying saucers, Mr. Stoddard. U.F.O.s.

30:04.402 --> 30:08.839
<i>You're rather well known in these parts for your
interest in the subject. We thought we could talk.</i>

30:08.907 --> 30:10.898
<i>Just don't say anything, Sam.</i>

30:10.975 --> 30:16.572
<i>- Well, you know, some people have
actually, uh, questioned my sanity- - Sam.!</i>

30:16.648 --> 30:21.347
<i>- for claiming these things, so, uh, forgive me if I have
a little, uh, reluctance to- - Totally understandable.</i>

30:21.419 --> 30:26.186
A few crackpots have poisoned the well for
anyone who's seriously interested in the subject.

30:26.257 --> 30:28.987
- And you two are seriously interested?
- Absolutely.

30:29.060 --> 30:33.724
Well, what do you want me to do? I mean, have
you seen something and you want me to confirm it?

30:33.798 --> 30:36.164
<i>I want you to clam up.
Not really.</i>

30:36.234 --> 30:39.965
The government just can't take chances,
what with the Cold War and all.

30:40.038 --> 30:44.600
<i>Our equipment can't see everything,
so we rely on citizens like yourself.</i>

30:44.676 --> 30:48.703
Well, what I saw,
or what I might have seen,

30:48.780 --> 30:51.010
I don't think it had anything
to do with the Russians.

30:51.082 --> 30:54.074
Oh, we believe that. But we have
to consider every possibility.

30:54.152 --> 30:56.279
You believe me?
Yes, sir.

30:56.354 --> 30:59.346
So you're saying that it's-

30:59.424 --> 31:03.383
Well, that seeing something unusual in the
sky doesn't necessarily make a person crazy.

31:03.461 --> 31:06.555
Have you seen a U.F.O.,
Mr. Stoddard?

31:06.631 --> 31:11.068
<i>Not one word. Zero. Zip. Zilch. Nada.</i>

31:11.135 --> 31:13.069
You know, uh,

31:13.137 --> 31:17.870
I really would like to talk to you,
but I've- I've had a very busy day.

31:17.942 --> 31:22.072
<i>I'm surprised. Our sources told us that
you'd be more than willing to cooperate.</i>

31:22.146 --> 31:25.411
Sources? What-What sources?

31:25.483 --> 31:27.576
You've been checking up on me?
We just want your cooperation.

31:27.652 --> 31:29.142
You do?
Yes, sir.

31:29.220 --> 31:33.088
That's what I want. Your cooperation. I'd like to
know a little something about Project Blue Book.

31:36.561 --> 31:38.495
That's classified information,

31:38.563 --> 31:40.155
<i>Mr. Stoddard.</i>

31:40.231 --> 31:45.134
But if your testimony turns out
the way we expect it will,

31:45.203 --> 31:49.606
<i>we might be able to influence our superiors
to share a summary with you.</i>

31:50.675 --> 31:54.202
Oh, that'd be great.
See, I told you you could-

31:54.279 --> 31:56.213
<i>Have faith in me.</i>

31:56.281 --> 31:58.442
Ziggy says don't trust 'em, Sam.
They're big-time nozzles.

31:58.516 --> 32:01.508
<i>Why don't we arrange to meet
tomorrow, somewhere comfortable,</i>

32:01.586 --> 32:03.520
given how much
you have to tell us.

32:03.588 --> 32:06.989
I'm sure the government wouldn't mind giving
you the royal treatment. Well, thank you.

32:07.058 --> 32:11.119
L- I'm sure you'll find that my observations
will be very detailed and accurate.

32:11.195 --> 32:13.129
All right, Pop. Oh,
Pop, we're proud of you.

32:13.197 --> 32:15.165
- See you tomorrow.
- Okay. Thank you.

32:15.233 --> 32:17.098
- I'll show you out.
- Ma'am.

32:26.144 --> 32:28.135
Thanks a lot.

32:32.550 --> 32:34.984
Let's talk.

32:35.053 --> 32:38.386
Thank you very much.
You can't imagine our relief.

32:38.456 --> 32:42.688
These situations are very difficult to evaluate.
What time tomorrow do you want to see him?

32:42.760 --> 32:46.355
I don't think we really need
to speak to him, Mr. Stoddard.

32:46.431 --> 32:50.959
But you said- Dr. Hardy and I have interviewed
hundreds of these so-called witnesses.

32:51.035 --> 32:53.731
We have yet to find a single one
whose facts make any sense at all.

32:53.805 --> 32:57.332
He seems like a sweet old man.
Reminds me of my dad.

32:57.408 --> 32:59.376
Then how the hell can you
lead him along that way?

32:59.444 --> 33:05.144
We thought the appointment idea might give you a chance
to take him to a care facility without him struggling.

33:05.216 --> 33:07.150
You told us you've
had trouble controlling him.

33:07.218 --> 33:10.710
We'll be heading back to D.C.
In the morning.

33:10.788 --> 33:13.985
Listen, be grateful
the hospital's so close.

33:14.058 --> 33:16.652
It makes visitation
so much easier.

33:18.563 --> 33:20.724
Good night.

33:30.408 --> 33:33.343
Did you see their faces when I
said Project Blue Book? Uh, yeah.

33:33.411 --> 33:35.379
Did you see them? I mean,
they were like- Yeah. Um-

33:35.446 --> 33:37.937
<i>Yeah, but I also saw Brando
in One-Eyed Jacks.</i>

33:38.016 --> 33:40.507
Never trust a face when
you can only see one side.

33:40.585 --> 33:42.917
All right. Okay.
What does Ziggy say?

33:42.987 --> 33:45.046
What does Ziggy- Oh.
Yeah.

33:45.123 --> 33:47.523
Uh, "Data inconclusive. "
Huh?

33:47.592 --> 33:53.189
"Data inconclusive"? I got a bad feeling about
this, Sam. Like my second wife. You know? Uh- Uh-

33:53.264 --> 33:55.255
Al-
What's her name?

33:55.333 --> 33:57.426
Yeah, yeah. Al. Al.
The Hungarian one?

33:57.502 --> 34:01.939
What about the data I gave you from the library?
I gave you four very specific activity periods.

34:02.006 --> 34:03.940
Oh, okay.
Oh, yeah. Okay.

34:04.008 --> 34:06.374
Well, in addition to your alleged sighting
- Yeah.

34:06.444 --> 34:11.973
There were two in '62, and then
there was one in June of'58. Just one?

34:12.050 --> 34:14.280
Yes. Well, they could
have missed the second one.

34:14.351 --> 34:18.721
And then there were two
on New Year's, January '55.

34:18.790 --> 34:22.054
Of course, that could have been champagne.
There's a pattern. There's a pattern, Al.

34:22.126 --> 34:25.118
Have Ziggy run a time-coordinated
collation of the sightings, okay? Okay.

34:25.196 --> 34:26.754
Hurry up.
Okay.

34:26.831 --> 34:30.766
<i>Come on. Please be right.
Please be right.</i>

34:31.902 --> 34:33.803
What? You're right,
there's a pattern.

34:33.871 --> 34:38.672
There's a sighting approximately
every 47.51 Earth months.

34:38.743 --> 34:41.303
Yeah? And then there's
a second sighting...

34:41.379 --> 34:44.177
three or four days after
the first one. Yes! Yes!

34:44.248 --> 34:47.978
Don't you see? That's it! They're coming back.
They're coming back. And it could happen any time.

34:48.052 --> 34:52.351
I'm gonna be here to confirm their visit. This is
unbelievable! Don't you understand what I'm saying?

34:52.422 --> 34:56.688
With everything we know now, and with Ziggy
- I mean, if we can make contact, right?

34:56.761 --> 34:59.787
<i>And you gotta presume that they have
some kind of a computer system, right?</i>

34:59.864 --> 35:04.460
<i>If Ziggy can hook up into that, the possibilities-
They're endless, right? We can go- I mean-</i>

35:05.570 --> 35:11.406
<i>You see, Project Blue Book has
Washington's top priority U.F.O. Research.</i>

35:11.476 --> 35:14.445
<i>I can't wait to get a look
at what they must have.</i>

35:14.512 --> 35:18.004
I'll even bet they'll want to
include my information with it.

35:19.884 --> 35:23.752
Boy, I can't wait
to tell those guys.

35:23.821 --> 35:26.153
Huh? I mean, to see
their faces when I'll tell 'em.

35:26.224 --> 35:28.852
They're gonna-
Charlemont State Hospital?

35:28.926 --> 35:31.554
Wh-What's goin' on? I
thought we were goin'- Dad.

35:31.629 --> 35:33.824
Aw, no. No! Dad, look,
don't make it harder.

35:33.898 --> 35:36.093
Don't! You're gonna get hurt.
Pop! You'll just make it worse!

35:36.167 --> 35:38.397
You're makin' a mistake!
You're gonna be all right.

35:38.469 --> 35:40.903
You're making a terrible mistake!
Please, Pop.

35:40.972 --> 35:42.906
<i>Make it easy on yourself.
Please.!</i>

35:42.974 --> 35:47.411
<i>Just let me go, plea-Ah.! Let me go.!</i>

35:47.478 --> 35:49.412
No, listen to me!
Come here!

35:49.480 --> 35:53.416
This is all wrong. Look, I was invited
to meet a team of government officials,

35:53.484 --> 35:55.418
not to come here.

35:55.486 --> 35:58.546
<i>But we are here.</i>

35:59.824 --> 36:01.815
Shall we get started?

36:13.271 --> 36:15.205
I studied your service record,
Mr. Stoddard.

36:15.273 --> 36:17.867
Most combat veterans would be eager
to help when their country called.

36:17.942 --> 36:20.536
How about when their country
kidnaps them and ties 'em up in bed?

36:20.611 --> 36:24.411
<i>Please understand.
This is our job- a government mission.</i>

36:24.482 --> 36:27.747
<i>Uh, Sam? Ohh.</i>

36:27.818 --> 36:31.049
- Oh, Sam, I wouldn't let 'em do that.
- Do I have a choice?

36:31.122 --> 36:34.455
- You made your choice last night.
- What's in the needle?

36:34.525 --> 36:38.222
<i>What's in the needle?
Sodium Pentothal.</i>

36:38.296 --> 36:43.131
A truth serum, widely used.
Short-acting, no lasting effects.

36:43.201 --> 36:46.762
No. No, Sam, don't let 'em give you that.
There's no telling what you'll say.

36:46.837 --> 36:49.738
<i>Uh, you could change history.
You could even doom Quantum Leap.</i>

36:49.807 --> 36:53.743
- Hold him down.
- Look, h-how could you do this? You're a doctor.

36:53.811 --> 36:57.406
You know, he's got a point. I didn't
join the air force to harass old men.

36:57.481 --> 37:00.575
You joined it, so follow
orders. Sam, say something!

37:00.651 --> 37:03.916
Tell 'em anything! Make it up if you have to!
But don't let 'em shoot you with that junk!

37:03.988 --> 37:06.821
<i>All right, all right. Look.</i>

37:06.891 --> 37:10.258
I saw a self-illuminated elliptical orb...

37:10.328 --> 37:15.095
<i>- roughly 15 meters on the long axis, 10 on the short.
- Record this.</i>

37:15.166 --> 37:17.930
<i>This was three nights ago,
correct?</i>

37:18.002 --> 37:20.266
- May 21.
- Right. Right.

37:20.338 --> 37:24.672
It hovered approximately
10 to 20 meters above the ground...

37:24.742 --> 37:28.473
- with no apparent means of propulsion.
- Wow. Photographic memory?

37:28.546 --> 37:31.845
He could be quoting from something he read.
Let's make sure.

37:31.916 --> 37:34.908
- No! No!
- No! Hey! You bastards!

37:34.986 --> 37:37.887
Gooshie, what am I gonna do now?

37:40.391 --> 37:42.689
Oh, boy.

37:45.529 --> 37:48.965
Could you believe
all those forms?

37:49.033 --> 37:52.002
Look, we had to do it.
I know, I know.

37:52.069 --> 37:55.732
Tim, don't blame me.
Some day you're gonna understand.

37:55.806 --> 37:59.708
It's okay, Dad. I caught him
talking to himself last night.

37:59.777 --> 38:02.507
Not just mumbling,
a whole conversation.

38:02.580 --> 38:07.313
Yeah. I've seen him do that too. It's
almost like he's got some imaginary friend.

38:07.385 --> 38:12.755
Maybe it runs in the family.
You had one when you were little.

38:12.823 --> 38:15.815
Oh, I just hope I never
have to put you in here.

38:19.730 --> 38:22.665
Hold on.
That's their car.

38:22.733 --> 38:26.032
<i>Whose? Your government guys. I thought you
said they were going back to Washington.</i>

38:26.103 --> 38:29.595
That's what they told me. It's a
blue sedan. It could be anybody's.

38:29.674 --> 38:33.542
With government plates?
Let's go see.

38:33.611 --> 38:36.910
<i>We are going to ask you
a series of questions.</i>

38:36.981 --> 38:40.075
<i>You will answer
all of them truthfully.</i>

38:40.151 --> 38:42.381
Do you understand?

38:44.021 --> 38:45.955
Truthfully.

38:46.023 --> 38:49.254
Let's start with something simple,
like your name.

38:49.327 --> 38:52.490
- No, Sam.
- Sam.

38:52.563 --> 38:57.159
<i>- Louder, please.
- Dr. Samuel Beckett.</i>

38:58.235 --> 39:01.329
- No.
- Think you gave him too much?

39:01.405 --> 39:06.001
- Do you know where you are?
- I'm in, uh, New Mexico.

39:06.077 --> 39:08.443
What is the date?

39:08.512 --> 39:12.539
May 1, 1999.

39:12.616 --> 39:18.384
<i>Gooshie, if I should suddenly, pop out of existence,
I wanna leave everything to my first wife, Beth.</i>

39:18.456 --> 39:20.424
Tell us about yourself,
Dr. Beckett.

39:20.491 --> 39:25.895
Born: 8%8%53.
Terrific.

39:25.963 --> 39:29.091
He's 13 years old?
Or 113.

39:29.166 --> 39:32.567
<i>Father's name:
John Samuel Beckett.</i>

39:32.636 --> 39:35.935
Mother's name:
Thelma Louise Beckett.

39:36.006 --> 39:39.066
<i>Social security number:</i>

39:41.045 --> 39:44.139
563-

39:44.215 --> 39:46.308
86-

39:47.351 --> 39:50.980
9801.

39:51.989 --> 39:54.287
<i>Department of Defense...</i>

39:54.358 --> 39:57.225
<i>Umbra clearance number:</i>

39:58.229 --> 40:01.721
004-002-

40:01.799 --> 40:04.825
02-016.

40:04.902 --> 40:09.362
<i>- Did you hear that?
- It's a coincidence. He was in the service.</i>

40:09.440 --> 40:12.932
In World War I.
Umbra is an operative code.

40:14.178 --> 40:18.239
- Why do you need a clearance?
- Hang in there, Sam. Hang in there.

40:18.315 --> 40:21.512
- Why do you need a clearance, Dr. Beckett?
- My project.

40:21.585 --> 40:23.576
No!

40:23.654 --> 40:25.588
<i>What is your project?</i>

40:25.656 --> 40:29.786
Project... Quantum Leap.

40:29.860 --> 40:33.125
- No! No! No!
- This project studies unidentified flying objects?

40:37.334 --> 40:39.461
Travel in time.

40:44.341 --> 40:48.368
<i>What is it?
Orderly. Medication.</i>

40:48.446 --> 40:52.849
<i>This patient is under private care.
Then can you sign my orders, please?</i>

40:53.918 --> 40:56.978
<i>- Just back off.
- Come on, Pop. Wake up.</i>

40:57.054 --> 40:59.488
- You're making a bad mistake, sir.
- I don't think so.

40:59.557 --> 41:01.491
Tim?
Yeah. Let's go.

41:01.559 --> 41:06.792
- You don't know what you're doing.
- We're taking my father away from you. What else do we need to know?

41:06.864 --> 41:10.391
- Let's get out of here. Can you walk?
- I'll do my best.

41:12.303 --> 41:17.468
<i>Anybody sticks his face out this door, I
swear to God I'll blow it right offhis head.</i>

41:21.111 --> 41:24.478
<i>God, you're heavy.</i>

41:24.548 --> 41:27.574
- Hey, you!
- This way!

41:33.958 --> 41:37.018
Sam. Sam. That
way. Pop, come on!

41:37.094 --> 41:39.654
No. No.
This way.

41:42.233 --> 41:45.066
Let's just rest here.
Pop, where are we goin'?

41:45.135 --> 41:46.830
Over the guardrail.

41:46.904 --> 41:49.702
Pop! Wait!
Dad, watch it. Be careful!

41:53.277 --> 41:56.804
<i>Come on, Sam.
God. Are we lost?</i>

41:56.881 --> 41:59.816
All right. Don't dawdle. You can't
dawdle. They're closing in on you.

41:59.884 --> 42:03.342
There's a creek down there.
We can follow it out of here.

42:03.420 --> 42:06.014
No. No, it-it-it's this way.

42:06.090 --> 42:08.581
Pop, ifTim says the creek
is there, it's there.

42:08.659 --> 42:10.684
Yeah. But we're not
supposed to go there. Dad!

42:10.761 --> 42:13.753
It's this way.
Where you been?

42:13.831 --> 42:16.698
- This is it.
- Are you sure?

42:16.767 --> 42:19.895
Yeah. I'm positive.
This is where they'll come.

42:19.970 --> 42:23.906
<i>- Far out, Pop. This is the spot from the other night.
- This is exactly what this is.</i>

42:23.974 --> 42:26.238
<i>Hey, hide!</i>

42:26.310 --> 42:30.110
<i>You gotta hide.! Hurry up.! Hide.! Hide.!
Hide.! All right! Come on! Come on! This way!</i>

42:30.180 --> 42:33.513
Mr. Stoddard.
Mr. Stoddard, we need to talk.

42:33.584 --> 42:35.643
Well, Dr. Jekyll
and Major Hyde, huh?

42:35.719 --> 42:39.246
Listen, try and find 'em,
you slime buckets.

42:39.323 --> 42:43.259
<i>You don't seriously plan on keeping
your father out here all night, do you?</i>

42:43.327 --> 42:47.525
You're interfering with an official U.S.
Government investigation. That can be a felony.

42:47.598 --> 42:50.999
What do I do? I don't know. We're
way outside the original history now.

42:51.068 --> 42:54.333
<i>You don't want to see your son and grandson
do time in a federal prison.</i>

42:58.709 --> 43:00.700
What are you doin'?

43:04.481 --> 43:06.472
Over here.

43:11.355 --> 43:14.791
You made the smart choice.

43:14.858 --> 43:17.088
Come on, sir.

43:18.329 --> 43:22.197
Let him go!

43:24.034 --> 43:27.868
Put the shotgun down, Son.
Don't be stupid.

43:29.740 --> 43:33.335
<i>The shot pattern on that gun
will certainly kill your father too.</i>

43:33.410 --> 43:36.004
Yeah, like you care!

43:37.047 --> 43:39.277
Let him go!

43:49.960 --> 43:53.396
<i>Well, I'll be, Dad.
You were right all along.</i>

43:53.464 --> 43:56.592
<i>A self-illuminated elliptical orb...</i>

43:56.667 --> 43:59.227
<i>approximately 15 meters
on the long axis,</i>

43:59.303 --> 44:01.237
<i>10 on the short.</i>

44:01.305 --> 44:03.739
<i>Hop aboard, Sam.
What?</i>

44:03.807 --> 44:09.143
<i>There's a 98.6% chance the old coot
is gonna take a ride ofhis lifetime.!</i>

44:21.625 --> 44:24.059
Hello!

44:27.431 --> 44:29.422
Bye, Pop.

44:48.686 --> 44:51.883
Hey! Hey! Hey!
What the hell you doin'?

44:54.858 --> 44:56.849
Kill the engine!
Shut it down!

44:56.927 --> 45:00.294
What, are you crazy?
You all right, Jimmy?

45:00.364 --> 45:03.231
Yeah, I'm fine. I'm sorry.
Everybody all right?

45:03.300 --> 45:05.495
<i>Yeah. We're all right.
Get him off there.</i>

45:05.569 --> 45:08.732
Didn't I tell you to stay away from the forklift?
You're not ready to drive it yet.

45:08.806 --> 45:13.766
Frank, is that you? Of course
it's me. Did you hit your head?

45:13.844 --> 45:18.872
No. No, I- No.
No, I didn't-

45:18.949 --> 45:21.110
Jimmy.

45:21.185 --> 45:25.315
Jimmy. I'm Jimmy.

45:25.389 --> 45:28.483
I know you'reJimmy.
And I'm back. I'm back, Frank.

45:28.559 --> 45:30.390
Ha! Look, I'm Jimmy!

45:31.495 --> 45:33.486
Oh, boy.

